All items are in stock at the time of listing. Should any item become out of stock the item will be re-ordered to fulfill the auction listing. Out-of-stock orders generally ship within 10-12 days.

Payment

The following payment options are available. Cash, Check, and Money Order payments are due within 10 days of auction close.

* Credit Card. Visa or Mastercard (no added fees) are accepted. Please see our website (www.spartan-arms.com), Gun Broker Checkout or call 901-491-9505 for payment information.
* We accept money orders, personal checks, or certified checks. Please allow 7-10 days for personal checks to clear. Please mail to: Spartan Arms, 5342 Cypress Hollow Drive. Lakeland, TN 38002
* We accept check by phone. Please call 901-491-9505 to complete.

Shipping

Shipping is UPS or USPS in the Continental U.S. We do not ship international. Orders shipped upon receipt of payment and FFL information. A tracking number or confirmation number can be provided by e-mail upon shipment, if requested.

* $35 for Long Guns.
* $25 for Handguns.
* Multiple items will ship together with only one shipping charge.
* Please add $15 additional for shipments to Alaska and Hawaii.

Product Guarantee

Warranties are handled by the manufacturer. Warranty claims need to be directed to the manufacturer, as warranties are between the owner (that's you) and the warrantor. However if you need service or warranty work on a new piece of equipment and need our help in accessing them, we will be glad to answer any questions or help you get in contact with the right party.

All used items are "as is" and no warranties are given or implied. No refunds on firearms if transferred. Inspect the weapon at the dealer! Shipping and Handling is not refundable. Most product photos are of the actual item. Occasionally we will use stock photos on our listing. Some serial numbers in the photos will not match the actual item.

Firearms are warrantied by the MANUFACTURER.

* All used items are "as is" and no warranties are given or implied by Spartan Arms.
* Once a firearm has been transferred, it is now used.
* All guns from Davidson's come with Davidson's lifetime warranty.

Product Returns

All sales are final. We do not accept Returns or exchanges. Please be sure that you are legally able to purchase the firearm in your area. Any purchases that cannot be accepted or are refused by the FFL will incurr a minimum $25 restocking fee for handguns and a minimum $35 restocking fee for Long guns.

The Polish ammo is hard core deep penetrating round, and it's sure fire, I've never had a bad round.  If you want to trade stright up, round for round, Polish for new production 7.62x25 ammo. If you like the Polish ammo and want to trade some new production ammo for it, let's do it.  This Polish stuff is almost becoming a collectible.  I almost hate to shoot it as a normal target round.  By the way the new production ammo uses a thin copper jacket, so it does not penatrate like the thick steel jacket on the Polish ammo.  Thanks, Mike

postcontent:
Barrett model 98B in .338 lapua magnum. This rifle is brand new in box and comes with a harris bipod. The USO scope and rings have been sold and are no longer available.

Carved from years of hard-earned insight, the Model 98B is entirely in a league of its own. Designed to adapt to a user’s every need, this revolutionary precision rifle offers long-range performance that others can only dream of.

Even the casual observer can see that the Model 98B is not a descendant of the bolt action sporting rifle. In fact, it’s not a descendant of anything. This .338 Lapua Magnum rifle was developed to be a completely unique, purpose-built platform for precise long-range shooting.

Thanks to its modular layout, this rifle can be adapted to fit each user’s exact needs. Its straight-line design, running from the muzzle to the shooter’s shoulder, tames recoil. It also allows for faster, more accurate follow-up shots fed from the 10-round detachable magazine. The ergonomic pistol grip reduces muscle fatigue and provides total control over the fully adjustable trigger. An intuitive, thumb-operated safety can be accessed without compromising the firing grip. This allows the shooter to maintain a solid weld to the adjustable cheek piece. The oversized bolt handle can be easily manipulated, feeding a fresh round into the chamber as the bolt silently glides through a polymer guide. 

The Model 98B rifle’s aluminum upper receiver boasts an 18-inch M1913 optics rail, offering plenty of space to mount substantial optics as well as a night vision device or other accessories. The forward receiver is drilled and tapped for accessory rails to be mounted at the 3, 6 and 9 o’clock positions. 

This impressive long-range weapon isn’t all work. Equipped with a rear monopod and forward bipod, it’s also a pleasure to shoot. From its highly efficient muzzle brake to its shooter-adaptable design and unprecedented performance, the 98B is ingenuity in action.

title: Want To Buy:  Denver Shooting Club, Thoughts?
location: Denver Metro and suburbs, Denver, Colorado
postcontent:
**Please take time to read through and leave helpful feedback**

Any hunter, target shooter or gun enthusiast who has lived in Denver knows that the capital city of one of the most gun/hunter friendly states provides few opportunities to maintain proficiency as a hunter or marksman. While there is a selection of shooting ranges in the city, albeit dwindling, many are considered to be over-priced, un-welcoming, or unsuitable for certain types of shooting (3-gun, quick draw, long range, etc.). The easiest alternative is to find private land with owners consent. However, few city-dwellers have easy contact with farmers and ranchers, and few farmers and ranchers are overly eager to have gun-toting city dwellers traipse about their land. That leaves public land, owned by the Department of Wildlife, the Forestry Department, or the Bureau of Land Management (BLM). One look at a government map of the state of Colorado shows an abundant supply of free-to-shoot land... on the western slope. Us Front-Rangers are mainly limited to Pawnee National Grasslands in the northeast, and Comanche in the south. I have personally been to both Pawnee and Comanche, and can testify that while they are both no-frills nothing-fancy areas to shoot, they are perfect for any activity you can think of, within the confines of the law, obviously. The only draw-back to Pawnee for Denver shooters is the drive. From Exit 1-25 exit 200, the shooting area I have visited was just around 90 miles away, and that was the well known "busy" area. There are more remote areas with longer distances to backdrops for distance shooters, but those may be another 20 miles away. For a solo outing to blow off some rounds or to dial in a rifle, a 160-200 mile round trip drive is less than ideal. Which made me ask; has anyone seen, heard of, or thought about a Denver Metro Shooting Club? I am not talking about a gun club with fees or weird initiations or mandatory meetings, I am think about something more relaxed and useful.
 The idea I have would be to make a Facebook page where people could simply post where they are going to shoot, when, for how long, and how many people they could take. Also, they could list what they might expect to help out with gas, as well as rules they would want to abide by. 
An example would be;

1 shooter going to Pawnee Sunday, August 26th. Departing Denver at 0930, will return home 1700. Have room for 3 more shooters. Would like $10 per passenger for fuel, or a box of 12ga or 5.56. No drinking, no littering.

I understand many are wary of strangers, but have to say everyone I have met on Armslist has been really cool so far. I've sold magazines to military veterans and purchased sights and rifles from active and retired law enforcement. I think that if we are honest about what the group could be, efficient car-pooling and friendly shooting with responsible individuals, this could be a success. It could also be a great way for hunters to network and make new hunting friends. Small-gamers could gain access to new prairie dog and rabbit land, and any friends of farmers can help their farmer friends out with a plethora of new responsible shooters. There will be no tolerance for the shooters that spend all afternoon drinking and shooting and leave hundreds of shotgun shells and dozens of beer cans littered about giving a bad name to shooters everywhere.

If something similar to what I have described already exists, I would love to know about it. Please feel free to email me at docneuey@gmail.com and let me know what kind of shooting you would like to do, and maybe a short paragraph including your shooting experience. If there is a strong enough response, I will take the next step in making this real.

Thanks so much for taking the time to read this. I would appreciate any feedback you may have.

-Mark

title: For Trade:  ** For trade only ** 7.62x25 1950's Polish Steel Jacket Ammo
location: 45min North of Columbus, Cardington OH, Columbus, Ohio
postcontent: I see Dealers have the old Polish surplus Ammo back in stock, but they are charging almost the same price as new production ammo, like S&B or Wolf.  I have a large quanty of 1950's Polish ammo in the 1260 Round Tins. What's nice about the Polish ammo is that it has a Steel Jacket that makes it almost like an Armor pericing round.  Most public target ranges will not let you shoot it, because it causes so much damage to there range.  The Polish ammo is hard core deep penetrating round, and it's sure fire, I've never had a bad round.  If you want to trade stright up, round for round, My Polish ammo for your new production 7.62x25 ammo.  I'll trade any amount you want.  I'm not a dealer, I bought it to shoot it, and I'm shooting up more every day.  But I just target shoot, and don't care about how good it penetrats.  If you like the Polish ammo and want to trade some new production ammo for it, let's do it.  This Polish ammo is almost becoming a collectible.  I hate to shoot it as a normal target round.  The new production ammo uses a thin copper jacket, so it does not penatrate like the thick steel jacket on the Polish ammo.  The Polish ammo is drying up, get it while you can.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Mossberg 44 U.S.
postcontent:
The Mossberg 44 is the U.S. 44 .22 caliber rifle manufactured by Mossberg for the U.S. Military. It is similar to the M42 and M44 commercial rifles and many parts are interchangeable. With the proper magazine, you can use .22 short, .22 long, and .22 LR in this rifle. Without the magazine, you can use it as a single-shot rifle, the magazine holds seven (7) rounds. The rifle has a bull barrel with recessed muzzle; the trigger is not adjustable, the front sight is fixed, and the rear sight is a micro-adjustable peepsight Mossberg S100, Mossberg S133, or Lyman 57 MS (and there may be other sights out there). The barrel is "lead-lapped" which is a process (as explained to me) that fills in the micro-cracks in the metal producing a very smooth surface with very little variance or imperfections. It is also very labor intensive and, as a result, expensive.
Manufactured approx. 1943-1946.
No magazine for it.
